thank you, seoul

yellow eggs and blue and red
in the grass and flower bed

looking at AI-generated post-photographic images from the past nine months, I often see a synthetic and shroomed up continuation of Arthur Tress

[let this be the bookend to that tulip post from san francisco earlier this month]

when AI becomes AGI, the machines may write their own history of art and AT will imaginably be the most influential 'silent generation’ photographer

as a mortal antidote to filters, photoshop or midjourney, here’s some Alfred Eisenstaedt

you may look to Eisenstaedt for a candid warmth and spontaneity seldom attempted and never achieved in current celebrity portraits

these days the press is definitely more polarized, but is it genuinely more critical?
ballpoint crossbows pointing out white specks on a darkroom print before analog touch-up ten years ago [but the photograph is from 2001]

the previous post had a boy
a boy in a striped skirt

as a follow-up, the first four jpegs today are collaborations with
or portraits of
performers who embodied aspects of both maleness and femaleness

the last five have made some viewers, often to my surprise, misgender the photographed person

not who you're having sex with, but 'queer' as being about 
the self that is at odds with everything around it and that has to invent and create and find a place to speak and to thrive and to live.
[bell hooks]

we used to think machine intelligence would be clinically precise and dry like a calculator
but the last year has demonstrated that young, intelligent computers – just like young, intelligent primates – improvise and confabulate like there’s no truth and no tomorrow
not my birthday
